In planning the tests it was assumed that the width of an open trench would not be an important variable and that, in fact, a small crack or slit would be sufficient to screen elastic waves. A few tests were performed to evaluate this assumption. A comparison of the amplitude reduction factor contour diagram of test PF-17-250 shown on
Figure 20 for a trench 0.33 foot wide with that of test PF-21-250 on Figure 21 for a trench 1.0 foot wide indicated that the increased width of a trench did not cause a significant change in either the magnitude of reduction or the shape of the screened zone . These results tend to confirm the assumption that trench width is not an important variable .
Another assumption made in planning this research program was that open trenches would be more effective than sheet-walls as surface wave barriers, but to satisfy the questions of many observers, a few sheet-wall barrier tests were performed. For the sheet-wall tests listed in Table VI 11, an aluminum sheet 3/16 inches thick, feet deep, and 8 feet long was used as the barrier. For comparison the length and depth of the sheet-wall barrier for test SF-6-250 shown on Figure 2 2 were the same as the length and depth of the trench barrier for test PF-17-250 shown on Figure 20. In general the sheet-wall barriers were not as effective in reducing amplitude of vertical ground displacement as the trench barriers.
 
CONCLUSIONS
Field tests were conducted to evaluate the effectiveness of open trenches in reducing the amplitude of vertical ground motion. Annular trenches surrounding the source of vibration were used in tests designated as Active Isolation. Straight trenches were used at a distance from the source but near an area to be shielded in tests designated as Passive Isolation. The parameters varied in the active isolation tests were: distance from the source to the centerline of the trench, R depth of trench, H ; and angular length of the trench, 9 . The parameters varied in the passive isolation tests were : distance from the source to the centerline of the trench, R  depth of the trench, H ; length of the trench L ; and width of the trench, W  
To compare various tests the geometrical parameters were expressed in a dimensionless form by relating them to the wave length of the Rayleigh wave .
Conclusions from Active Isolation Tests
For full circle trenches at R/NR distances from 0.222 to
0.910 and for H/RR depths between 0.222 and 1.82, the following conclusions were made:
(1)	A minimum depth of H/Ä. 0.6 was required for a trench to satisfy the amplitude reduction criterion of 0.25
(2)	The zone screened by a full circle trench (9 - 360 0 ) extended to a distance of at least 10 wave lengths (10k ) from the source of excitation,
-51-
-52-
(3 ) Within the screened zone there was a specific distance from the source at which a "principal minimum" in amplitude reduction factor occurred and in these tests the "principal minimum" occurred at 2.2kR to 6 . 14k from the source, ( 14 ) The distance from the source to the "principal minimum" decreased with increasing trench depth.
For partial circle trenches at distance R/X, from 0.222 to
0.910 and for depths H/N between 0.222 and 1.82, the following conelusions were made:
(l ) A minimum depth of H//ÄR 0.6 was required for a trench to provide a screened zone with an amplitude reduction factor of 0.25,
(2 ) The zone screened by a partial circle trench was defined as the area outside the trench, extending to at least
10 wave lengths (IOÄ.R) from the source, and was bounded on the sides by radial lines from the center of the source through points from the ends of the trench,
	(3 ) Partial circle trenches of angular length, 9	less than
90 0 did not provide an effectively screened zone,
(h ) Amplification or "focusing" of vibratory energy occurred in the direction of the open side of the trench.
Conclusions from Passive Isolation Tests
From field model tests using straight open trenches (R/k 2.22 to 9.10 and H/x to 3.4) the following conclusions were reached:
 
(1)	Generally, larger trenches were required at greater distances from the source to accomplish a given amplitude
reduction,
(2)	Energy focusing or magnification of vertical motion occurred in zones in front of trenches and to the side of
trenches,
(3 ) Sheet-wall barriers were not as effective as open trenches in screening surface waves,
( u ) Trench width had little influence on the effectiveness of open trenches for W//Ä. between 0.13 to 0.91. 

